03918nam a22006855i 9780292761803DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211997txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927618037 a10.7560/7814432doi  a(DE-B1597)588015  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGR115b.T34 1997 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a398/.3532201 aTaggart, James M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Bear and His Sons :bMasculinity in Spanish and Mexican Folktales /cJames M. Taggart. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (356 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. "The Bear's Son" in Spain -- t3. "The Bear's Son" in Mexico -- t4. Tricksters in Spain -- t5. Tricksters in Mexico -- t6. "Blood Brothers" -- t7. "The Two Travelers" -- t8. Florencio's "Blancaflor" -- t9. Nacho's "Blancaflor" -- t10. "Orpheus" -- t11. Conclusions -- tAppendix: "The Bear's Son" in Spanish and Nahuat -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAll the world over, people tell stories to express their deepest feelings about such things as what makes a "real" man or woman; what true love, courage, or any other virtue is; what the proper relationships are between people. Often groups of people widely separated by space or time will tell the same basic story, but with differences in the details that reveal much about a particular group's worldview. This book looks at differences in the telling of several common Hispanic folktales. James Taggart contrasts how two men—a Spaniard and an Aztec-speaking Mexican—tell such tales as "The Bear's Son." He explores how their stories present different ways of being a man in their respective cultures. Taggart's analysis contributes to a revision of Freud's theory of gender, which was heavily grounded in biological determinism. Taggart focuses instead on how fathers reproduce different forms of masculinity in their sons. In particular, he shows how fathers who care for their infant sons teach them a relational masculinity based on a connected view of human relationships. Thus, The Bear and His Sons will be important reading not only in anthropology and folklore, but also in the growing field of men's studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCommunication in folklorezMexico. 0aMachismozMexicovFolklore. 0aMasculinityzMexicovFolklore. 0aMexicansvFolklore. 0aNahuasvFolklore. 0aTaleszMexico. 0aTaleszSpain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78144340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761803/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK